1
00:00:49,502 --> 00:00:51,493
<i>[Hawkeye] All right, give me a clamp.</i>

2
00:00:51,571 --> 00:00:55,234
<i>[Operating Room Chatter]</i>

3
00:00:58,845 --> 00:01:02,246
Hey, Hawk, what's this one?

4
00:01:02,315 --> 00:01:06,809
## [Humming]

5
00:01:08,154 --> 00:01:10,145
- "Avalon."
- Wrong.

6
00:01:10,223 --> 00:01:12,919
- "In a Little Spanish Town."
- Right.

7
00:01:12,992 --> 00:01:17,190
- Please, I'm right in the middle of a stomach.
- Try this one.

8
00:01:17,263 --> 00:01:20,061
## [Humming]

9
00:01:21,801 --> 00:01:26,829
- "On Wisconsin."
- No. That was "O Shepherd, Guide Thy Flock."

10
00:01:26,906 --> 00:01:29,932
Oh, I should've guessed that.
I've danced to that 1,000 times.

11
00:01:30,009 --> 00:01:32,000
Shut up, will ya? Shut up! Shut up!

12
00:01:32,078 --> 00:01:35,445
You shut up, Frank!
Everybody in this madhouse, shut up.

13
00:01:35,515 --> 00:01:39,451
We're a little late, folks. So good night
from <i>Name That Tune.</i> Clamp.

14
00:01:42,655 --> 00:01:44,589
- Colonel?
- Yo?

15
00:01:44,657 --> 00:01:46,818
Do you know what I found
in this morning's mail?

16
00:01:46,893 --> 00:01:49,885
Uh, now that's a tough one.
Hum a few bars, will you, Radar?

17
00:01:49,963 --> 00:01:52,227
[Chuckles] You're going home.

18
00:01:53,299 --> 00:01:55,062
I'm going home?

19
00:01:55,134 --> 00:01:57,432
You got all your points.
They're discharging you.

20
00:01:57,503 --> 00:02:00,700
- Discharged?
- To Tokyo, San Francisco, then home.

21
00:02:00,773 --> 00:02:04,504
I'm going home. I'm discharged.

22
00:02:04,577 --> 00:02:06,306
I'm going... I'm going home.

23
00:02:06,379 --> 00:02:09,644
- Henry, that's terrific.
- Henry, congratulations. That's terrific.

24
00:02:09,716 --> 00:02:12,742
- That's wonderful, sir.
- [All Congratulating]

25
00:02:12,819 --> 00:02:16,778
All together now.
# O, shepherd #

26
00:02:16,856 --> 00:02:22,556
[All] # Guard Wisconsin
Fight right through that line #

27
00:02:22,629 --> 00:02:26,963
I'm going home.
I can't believe it. I'm going home.

28
00:02:27,033 --> 00:02:30,025
Wow.

29
00:02:30,103 --> 00:02:34,096
- [Exhales] Oh boy, that's a "burny."
- [Laughs]

30
00:02:34,173 --> 00:02:36,141
- You sure you don't want a drink, Radar?
- No, sir.

31
00:02:36,209 --> 00:02:38,769
It makes my eyes turn red,
and I fall down.

32
00:02:38,845 --> 00:02:42,337
- It's kind of nice to lie down with red eyes.
- Yeah.

33
00:02:42,415 --> 00:02:44,747
Ooh, you wanted to make
that phone call to your wife.

34
00:02:44,817 --> 00:02:47,251
Oh, right, right.

35
00:02:47,320 --> 00:02:50,483
Now, let's see, Radar.
We're a day ahead plus 14 hours, right?

36
00:02:50,556 --> 00:02:53,457
No, sir. The States
are a day ahead plus 14 hours.

37
00:02:53,526 --> 00:02:55,858
- Well, then, it's yesterday in Bloomington?
- Yes, sir.

38
00:02:55,928 --> 00:02:57,862
Well, then, I should have
called her yesterday.

39
00:02:57,930 --> 00:03:00,091
Well, you didn't even
know about it then.

40
00:03:00,166 --> 00:03:02,498
Why can't everybody
be on the same time?

41
00:03:02,568 --> 00:03:05,059
Because the Earth is round,
keeps rotating all the time.

42
00:03:05,138 --> 00:03:07,129
Oh. I thought it was just an army thing.

43
00:03:07,206 --> 00:03:11,540
Let's see, Bloomington.
It's 1:00 Wednesday afternoon right now, sir.

44
00:03:11,611 --> 00:03:14,739
- 1:00? Lorraine's not home.
- Yes, sir.

45
00:03:14,814 --> 00:03:16,805
Maybe she just went
to the store or something.

46
00:03:16,883 --> 00:03:21,217
No, no. Every Wednesday she gets together
with Ella, Bea, Marie and Olive.

47
00:03:21,287 --> 00:03:24,450
They go out Route 26
to the Old Red Barn for lunch.

48
00:03:24,524 --> 00:03:26,549
They have two daiquiri's,
a watercress sandwich...

49
00:03:26,626 --> 00:03:30,562
and then Olive tells
all about her hysterectomy.

50
00:03:30,630 --> 00:03:33,428
- Every Wednesday, sir?
- It's a club.

51
00:03:33,499 --> 00:03:35,831
Well, how long do they usually stay?

52
00:03:35,902 --> 00:03:40,066
Oh, a couple hours. Then they kill an hour
on the way back feeling yarn at the knit shop.

53
00:03:40,139 --> 00:03:43,472
Well then, why don't you call Mrs. Blake
around 4:00 in the afternoon?

54
00:03:43,543 --> 00:03:48,537
Well, no. Olive usually gets carsick.
Better make it 4:30.

55
00:03:48,614 --> 00:03:50,605
Uh, just to be on the safe side,
we'll make it 5:00.

56
00:03:50,683 --> 00:03:55,177
No. Andrew has a trombone lesson at 5:00.
He's learning to play Ravel's <i>Bolero.</i>

57
00:03:55,254 --> 00:03:57,415
- I won't be able to hear a thing.
- 5:30?

58
00:03:57,490 --> 00:04:01,085
- 5:30. 5:30.
- Okay. 5:30.

59
00:04:01,160 --> 00:04:06,154
Radar, Lorraine and the kids
are going to die.

60
00:04:07,767 --> 00:04:10,930
You know, the first night I'm home...

61
00:04:11,003 --> 00:04:13,028
after we, uh, put the kiddos to bed?

62
00:04:15,074 --> 00:04:17,736
Lorraine and I
are going upstairs to our room.

63
00:04:19,412 --> 00:04:25,078
That woman has the most fantastic body
in downstate Illinois.

64
00:04:25,151 --> 00:04:28,814
Thirty-six, twenty-four, thirty-four.

65
00:04:28,888 --> 00:04:31,322
With skin like alabaster:

66
00:04:31,390 --> 00:04:35,383
Clear, soft, smooth and warm.

67
00:04:35,461 --> 00:04:38,794
And she wears those
little, short, flimsy nighties.

68
00:04:42,468 --> 00:04:45,904
I think I will have that drink, sir.

69
00:04:46,005 --> 00:04:50,135
Finally. Finally, you're going
to command this outfit.

70
00:04:50,209 --> 00:04:52,143
Everything's happening so fast.

71
00:04:52,211 --> 00:04:56,875
Discipline. Adherence to regulations.
A taut ship.

72
00:04:56,949 --> 00:04:59,281
I love tautness.

73
00:04:59,352 --> 00:05:03,254
- To command is your destiny.
- [Giggles]

74
00:05:03,322 --> 00:05:07,224
Oh, I can feel the power
surging through your veins.

75
00:05:07,293 --> 00:05:11,286
- Am I really surging?
- Oh, Frank, you'll be magnificent.

76
00:05:11,364 --> 00:05:14,356
I just wish I'd taken
R.O.T.C. In school.

77
00:05:14,433 --> 00:05:17,493
- I wasted so much time in the stamp club.
- I thought you were President?

78
00:05:17,570 --> 00:05:20,403
Well, that wasn't leadership.
They needed someone to lick the stamps...

79
00:05:20,473 --> 00:05:22,634
and I had the biggest tongue.

80
00:05:22,708 --> 00:05:25,700
- Frank, do you doubt your ability?
- Mmm.

81
00:05:25,778 --> 00:05:29,612
Do you want to see how sure
I am of your ability?

82
00:05:29,682 --> 00:05:33,243
Well, all great men have their doubts.
They say going up San Juan Hill...

83
00:05:33,319 --> 00:05:35,514
Teddy Roosevelt was worried sick
about breaking his glasses.

84
00:05:35,588 --> 00:05:37,579
Look, darling.

85
00:05:39,826 --> 00:05:42,659
I've been saving it for you.

86
00:05:42,728 --> 00:05:45,458
Well, I haven't been
promoted yet, Margaret.

87
00:05:45,531 --> 00:05:48,557
Out goes Major Burns.

88
00:05:48,634 --> 00:05:52,001
In comes Colonel Burns.

89
00:05:54,707 --> 00:05:56,834
- [Excited Laughter] Yes?
- Margaret?

90
00:05:56,909 --> 00:05:59,434
I think I'm surging.

91
00:05:59,579 --> 00:06:03,015
Lorraine, is that you? It's me.

92
00:06:03,082 --> 00:06:06,449
I got good news, honey.
I'm coming home.

93
00:06:06,519 --> 00:06:11,513
Honest. For good. Yeah, the orders
just came through this morning.

94
00:06:11,591 --> 00:06:15,493
I oughta be coming through
the front door in about three days.

95
00:06:15,561 --> 00:06:20,328
Honey... aw, please don't do that.
Honey, please.

96
00:06:20,399 --> 00:06:23,630
- She crying?
- No, she wants to re-cover the furniture.

97
00:06:25,104 --> 00:06:27,038
Honey, I just wanna see you and the kids.

98
00:06:27,106 --> 00:06:30,598
I don't care what the furniture
looks like, except for the bed.

99
00:06:32,845 --> 00:06:36,747
- Now she's crying.
- Sir, there's a time limit on the call.

100
00:06:36,816 --> 00:06:40,912
Honey, now just take it easy, okay?
Good.

101
00:06:40,987 --> 00:06:45,151
Are the kids home?
She is? Well, put her on.

102
00:06:47,059 --> 00:06:50,222
Janie-poo? It's Daddy.

103
00:06:50,296 --> 00:06:54,096
Num-num-num-num-num.
I'm eating you up.

104
00:06:54,166 --> 00:06:57,158
- Sir, there isn't too much time.
- Leave him alone. He's eating.

105
00:06:57,236 --> 00:07:00,797
Janie, honey, would you get Mommy
back on the phone?

106
00:07:00,873 --> 00:07:04,536
Oh, and, uh, tell Andy
to stop playing Ravel's <i>Bolero.</i>

107
00:07:06,279 --> 00:07:11,216
Lorraine, honey, listen.
Now, there's a lot of things you have to do.

108
00:07:11,284 --> 00:07:14,276
Well, like, uh... My-My suits.

109
00:07:14,353 --> 00:07:16,685
See, I've lost a lot of weight over here.

110
00:07:16,756 --> 00:07:21,216
I mean, I'm uh, I'm a 34-waist now.
You won't know me stripped.

111
00:07:21,294 --> 00:07:23,285
Wear your dog tags.

112
00:07:23,362 --> 00:07:27,025
Honey, the brown double-breasted.
It might fit now.

113
00:07:27,099 --> 00:07:29,465
So just take it to the cleaners.

114
00:07:29,535 --> 00:07:34,905
Uh... She... Honey, I don't want
your mother wearing my suits.

115
00:07:36,008 --> 00:07:39,671
She what? Well, that's dumb.

116
00:07:39,745 --> 00:07:42,805
She went to a party
dressed as Conrad Nagel.

117
00:07:42,882 --> 00:07:46,374
- That's it, sir.
- Honey, I gotta go.

118
00:07:46,452 --> 00:07:49,285
Now, Lorraine, don't tell anybody.

119
00:07:49,355 --> 00:07:51,721
We'll just walk into
the country club Saturday night...

120
00:07:51,791 --> 00:07:54,624
start dancing and let 'em all cheer.

121
00:07:54,694 --> 00:07:59,529
Lorraine? Lorraine? We got cut off.

122
00:08:01,634 --> 00:08:05,400
[Exhales]
Sweet Lorraine.

123
00:08:05,471 --> 00:08:09,430
[Whispering]
She has a fantastic body.

124
00:08:20,482 --> 00:08:23,144
Okay, Radar. Everything
in these boxes is to be shipped.

125
00:08:23,218 --> 00:08:25,209
- My uniforms go in the bag.
- Check.

126
00:08:25,287 --> 00:08:27,278
Check-a-roony in a banana-ka.

127
00:08:29,157 --> 00:08:31,591
Is there one or two "Js"
in "fragile," sir?

128
00:08:31,660 --> 00:08:34,823
Uh, one will do it, Radar.

129
00:08:34,896 --> 00:08:38,229
- There it is.
- You find something, sir?

130
00:08:38,300 --> 00:08:41,963
Yeah, that jar of mayonnaise
we lost last Fourth ofJuly.

131
00:08:42,037 --> 00:08:44,972
Hey, you better write a letter of apology
to that navy chaplain.

132
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:48,532
I thought he copped it.
[Whistles] Boy, that's a greeny.

133
00:08:52,214 --> 00:08:55,741
Oh... Hey, hey, hey.

134
00:08:55,817 --> 00:08:57,842
There's a picture of you and me, Radar.

135
00:08:57,919 --> 00:09:03,482
Oh. Oh, that's right after
you took out my appendix.

136
00:09:03,558 --> 00:09:06,049
Mmm. You were one sick kid.

137
00:09:06,128 --> 00:09:08,460
You know, I looked for that thing
till 4:00 in the morning.

138
00:09:08,530 --> 00:09:12,694
- It was behind your secum.
- I didn't put it there on purpose, sir.

139
00:09:16,705 --> 00:09:19,868
- You saved my life.
- Ah, my pleasure, Radar.

140
00:09:22,377 --> 00:09:24,038
- <i>Um, sir?</i>
- Yo?

141
00:09:24,112 --> 00:09:26,171
There's something I'd like to tell you.

142
00:09:26,248 --> 00:09:29,513
Well, now, you've got
exactly 34 hours to tell me.

143
00:09:29,584 --> 00:09:34,078
Yeah. Well, uh...

144
00:09:34,156 --> 00:09:36,886
I just wanted to say
that I'm really gonna miss you.

145
00:09:36,958 --> 00:09:41,952
Um, you know, my own father
didn't have me until he was 63.

146
00:09:42,030 --> 00:09:46,023
And, uh, first time we played peek-a-boo
together, he had a stroke.

147
00:09:49,237 --> 00:09:53,071
Look, uh, Radar, don't get gushy, okay?
You know how I am.

148
00:09:53,141 --> 00:09:58,909
Oh, yeah. Well, um, anyway,
I made something for you.

149
00:09:58,980 --> 00:10:02,143
- Oh.
- You know how you're always losing your keys?

150
00:10:02,217 --> 00:10:04,151
- Yeah.
- Well... [Clears Throat]

151
00:10:04,219 --> 00:10:07,552
This is a key chain,
and the cartridge is a fob.

152
00:10:07,622 --> 00:10:11,114
- Well, hey, Radar, this is terrific.
- Thank you.

153
00:10:11,193 --> 00:10:14,162
- It's inscribed in writing.
- Oh... Oh.

154
00:10:14,229 --> 00:10:17,824
Um, "To Colonel H. B<i>...</i>

155
00:10:17,899 --> 00:10:22,802
from Corp. O'R., Korea, 1952.

156
00:10:24,172 --> 00:10:26,834
Hey, you know,
the workmanship on this is beautiful.

157
00:10:26,908 --> 00:10:30,571
- It's a Winchester.
- Well, thanks, Radar.

158
00:10:30,645 --> 00:10:34,172
Um, I was gonna get you a bamboo flute,
but they only had three-holers.

159
00:10:36,585 --> 00:10:39,577
[Clears Throat] Oh...

160
00:10:42,157 --> 00:10:45,854
- This was my father's. It's yours.
- Oh?

161
00:10:45,927 --> 00:10:48,919
- For keeps?
- Sure.

162
00:10:51,500 --> 00:10:53,434
Oh, wow.

163
00:10:55,604 --> 00:10:59,096
Oh, gee, what a beautiful thermometer.

164
00:11:01,443 --> 00:11:05,607
- It isn't oral, is it?
- No.

165
00:11:05,680 --> 00:11:10,344
He used to say, "If you want accuracy,
go right to the horse's mouth."

166
00:11:10,418 --> 00:11:12,386
He was a stickler for accuracy.

167
00:11:12,454 --> 00:11:16,823
- Yeah, I'll bet.
- Yeah. [Clears Throat]

168
00:11:18,159 --> 00:11:21,458
Well, um, thank you for everything, sir.

169
00:11:21,530 --> 00:11:26,524
Thank you, Radar. Hey, come on, now.
Let's get on the stick.

170
00:11:26,601 --> 00:11:29,365
- Yes, sir. I'll get this right out of the way.
- [Clears Throat]

171
00:11:33,208 --> 00:11:35,733
[Chattering]

172
00:11:35,810 --> 00:11:39,803
- Oh, try this. Try this.
- This is great.

173
00:11:39,881 --> 00:11:41,815
- You didn't try this yet.
- Terrific.

174
00:11:41,883 --> 00:11:45,478
Take that. Isn't that good?

175
00:11:45,554 --> 00:11:48,387
[Henry] Now, that's good.
Hey, now that's delicious.

176
00:11:48,456 --> 00:11:50,788
- [Laughing]
- What is that?

177
00:11:50,859 --> 00:11:52,690
- Sea snails.
- Sea snails?

178
00:11:52,761 --> 00:11:57,164
- By the "snee" shore. [Laughing]
- [Laughing]

179
00:11:57,232 --> 00:12:01,100
[Laughing]
Did you hear what he said?

180
00:12:01,169 --> 00:12:05,128
[Slurring]
Okay. Oopsy. All gone.

181
00:12:05,206 --> 00:12:07,936
I'll get... I'll get some more.

182
00:12:08,009 --> 00:12:10,273
- Garçon, more booze.
- [Banging Sound]

183
00:12:10,345 --> 00:12:13,178
- <i>What is that? I didn't have that.</i>
- <i>You got a plateful.</i>

184
00:12:13,248 --> 00:12:15,910
- <i>Look at it.</i>
- <i>[Henry] Oh, here she comes.</i>

185
00:12:15,984 --> 00:12:19,283
- Six bucks, tax included.
- [Hawkeye, Trapper] I got it.

186
00:12:19,354 --> 00:12:21,117
- I got it. Come on. It's my party.
- No, I got it.

187
00:12:21,189 --> 00:12:24,681
- I got it.
- I'll tell you what, we'll flip.

188
00:12:24,759 --> 00:12:27,250
Tails, you lose.
Here you go, Mama-san.

189
00:12:27,329 --> 00:12:30,856
<i>Thank you.</i>
<i>Just keep everything coming.</i>

190
00:12:30,932 --> 00:12:34,595
<i>Hey, now listen, guys.</i>
<i>Guys, you cannot pay for any more booze.</i>

191
00:12:34,669 --> 00:12:36,933
I'm the one that's going home.

192
00:12:37,005 --> 00:12:40,031
- Henry, we're giving you this party.
- Mm.

193
00:12:40,108 --> 00:12:42,872
- You know why?
- Because I'm going home.

194
00:12:42,944 --> 00:12:46,573
Wrong. Because you're
one hell of a human being.

195
00:12:46,648 --> 00:12:49,640
- One hell of a human being.
- I got it.

196
00:12:49,718 --> 00:12:53,381
We're past that part. Now we're up to
"one helluva human being."

197
00:12:53,455 --> 00:12:57,289
- I'll tell you who's one helluva human being.
- Mm-hmm.

198
00:12:57,359 --> 00:13:01,022
You guys are one helluva of a human being.
That's what you guys are.

199
00:13:01,096 --> 00:13:04,429
- I'll drink to that.
- Let's all drink to that.

200
00:13:04,499 --> 00:13:08,697
There we go.
[Exhales Loudly]

201
00:13:11,806 --> 00:13:14,741
How you doing, Henry?

202
00:13:14,809 --> 00:13:20,270
I gotta go to the "toidy"
is how I'm doing. [Laughs]

203
00:13:20,348 --> 00:13:24,808
But, can I find it
is what I don't know.

204
00:13:26,488 --> 00:13:29,821
[Laughing]
You go... You go...

205
00:13:29,891 --> 00:13:32,291
- You go out the back door, hmm?
- Okay.

206
00:13:32,360 --> 00:13:36,353
You come to a big tree.
You pass the big tree.

207
00:13:36,431 --> 00:13:41,266
You go to a second tree.
The toidy is the third tree.

208
00:13:41,336 --> 00:13:44,499
The third tree is the toidy.
[Laughing]

209
00:13:44,572 --> 00:13:48,599
[Hysterical Laughter]
The toidy tree.

210
00:13:48,677 --> 00:13:51,111
Thank God forJoyce Kilmer.

211
00:13:51,179 --> 00:13:54,671
Hey, uh, speaking of trees...

212
00:13:54,749 --> 00:13:58,082
you know, I'm really
gonna miss you guys.

213
00:13:58,153 --> 00:14:01,350
I mean that.
I'm really gonna miss you guys.

214
00:14:01,423 --> 00:14:04,187
<i>I wish we could all go home together.</i>

215
00:14:04,259 --> 00:14:07,592
- Henry, we had a lot of laughs together.
- Hmm?

216
00:14:10,098 --> 00:14:14,262
- [Laughing]
- What? What? What?

217
00:14:14,335 --> 00:14:18,032
Remember that time that Father Mulcahy
caught you in your tent...

218
00:14:18,106 --> 00:14:22,634
- with that lady war correspondent, huh?
- [Both Laughing]

219
00:14:22,711 --> 00:14:24,872
[Laughing]

220
00:14:24,946 --> 00:14:30,475
You said you were giving an interview
on the importance of clean underwear.

221
00:14:38,493 --> 00:14:40,688
I can't wait. Which tree is it?

222
00:14:40,762 --> 00:14:43,731
<i>[Trapper]</i>
<i>Number one is for number two.</i>

223
00:14:43,798 --> 00:14:49,031
And number three
is for number one.

224
00:14:49,104 --> 00:14:52,335
Number four is the ladies' tree.
Don't go there.

225
00:14:52,407 --> 00:14:55,808
Okay, 'scuse me. [Laughing]

226
00:14:55,877 --> 00:15:00,211
- Oh, that's a burny.
- Oh. Here we go.

227
00:15:01,983 --> 00:15:04,816
- [Whooping]
- [All Laughing]

228
00:15:07,522 --> 00:15:10,355
Okay. Hey, now.

229
00:15:10,425 --> 00:15:12,825
- Hey, Kim? Hey.
- Kim?

230
00:15:12,894 --> 00:15:15,727
- What, what, what?
- Ow.

231
00:15:15,797 --> 00:15:18,630
- Here's the box.
- [Groans]

232
00:15:18,700 --> 00:15:21,533
Now you girls know what to do.
Come on, ladies. Over here.

233
00:15:21,603 --> 00:15:26,563
- Over there, girls.
- <i>Over there. You know what to do, right?</i>

234
00:15:26,641 --> 00:15:28,632
- Right?
- Stand up straight.

235
00:15:28,710 --> 00:15:31,144
I'm standing straight.
The country's crooked.

236
00:15:31,212 --> 00:15:33,077
Shh! Here he comes.

237
00:15:35,250 --> 00:15:38,570
- Oh, my gosh.
- Henry, you okay?

238
00:15:38,704 --> 00:15:41,901
Oh, fine.

239
00:15:41,973 --> 00:15:45,272
But a lot of bark
came off ol' number three.

240
00:15:45,344 --> 00:15:46,834
[Laughing]

241
00:15:46,912 --> 00:15:49,574
- [Laughing]
- <i>[Hawkeye] Don't sit down. Don't sit down.</i>

242
00:15:49,648 --> 00:15:52,014
What, what, what, what?

243
00:15:52,084 --> 00:15:54,917
Attention!

244
00:15:54,986 --> 00:15:57,978
- We're drumming you out of the military.
- Hot dog.

245
00:15:58,056 --> 00:16:03,255
- Radar, cue the band.
- ##<i>[Humming "America"]</i>

246
00:16:03,328 --> 00:16:06,058
- Lieutenant Colonel Henry Blake?
- Yo?

247
00:16:06,131 --> 00:16:09,999
By virtue of the power of the authority
vested in me...

248
00:16:10,068 --> 00:16:13,231
- by Rosey's Bar and Grill and Pro Station.
- Mm-hmm.

249
00:16:13,305 --> 00:16:15,967
And in the presence of those present
who have faithfully served...

250
00:16:16,041 --> 00:16:19,875
- under your barely distinguishable command.
- Mm-hmm.

251
00:16:19,945 --> 00:16:24,678
- I hereby disrupt you of all military rank.
- Okay.

252
00:16:24,750 --> 00:16:28,379
- ## [Continues]
- <i>Captain Mclntyre, would you</i>
<i>do the dishonors, please?</i>

253
00:16:28,453 --> 00:16:30,887
From this day henceward...

254
00:16:30,956 --> 00:16:36,622
- you will known as Mister Dr. Henry Blake.
- [Chuckles]

255
00:16:36,695 --> 00:16:40,028
[Chuckling Continues]

256
00:16:42,567 --> 00:16:47,061
[All Laughing]

257
00:16:47,139 --> 00:16:50,973
<i>And now, here's a box.</i>

258
00:16:51,042 --> 00:16:53,977
- A box. I got a box.
- [Laughing]

259
00:16:54,045 --> 00:16:55,979
- Don't open it now.
- What, what, what?

260
00:16:56,047 --> 00:17:00,381
Henry, it's civvies. We had the whole thing
handmade for you in Seoul.

261
00:17:00,452 --> 00:17:04,286
- Ahh...
- The tie is silk. Handmade by a worm.

262
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:09,350
- Ohh, guys, guys, guys, guys.
- Radar, kill the band.

263
00:17:09,428 --> 00:17:12,420
- ## [Stops]
- Take five.

264
00:17:12,497 --> 00:17:14,988
- Were you surprised, sir? Were you? Was he?
- Well...

265
00:17:16,735 --> 00:17:18,669
- Do you know what is in that box?
- What?

266
00:17:18,737 --> 00:17:22,229
- A brand new suit.
- [Gasps]

267
00:17:23,642 --> 00:17:26,475
How did you know my size?

268
00:17:26,545 --> 00:17:29,776
I traced you when you were asleep.

269
00:17:31,149 --> 00:17:34,312
Let's get into uniform
and play "Assembly," soldier.

270
00:17:34,386 --> 00:17:38,413
- Sir, I'm getting a cold sore.
- Well, Captain Ahab only had one leg.

271
00:17:38,490 --> 00:17:40,651
Well, he wasn't in the army, sir.
He was a whale guy.

272
00:17:40,725 --> 00:17:45,992
- Play it!
- ## [Reveille]

273
00:17:46,064 --> 00:17:49,556
- Ow.
- ## [Continues]

274
00:17:52,571 --> 00:17:57,099
- Are you sure that was "Assembly?"
- As close as I can come, sir.

275
00:17:57,175 --> 00:17:59,302
It's really "Sleepy Lagoon" played fast.

276
00:17:59,377 --> 00:18:03,370
- Ah, forget it. [Blows Whistle]
- Yes, sir.

277
00:18:05,383 --> 00:18:08,875
Company, fall in! On the double!

278
00:18:08,954 --> 00:18:11,445
[Blows Whistle]

279
00:18:13,191 --> 00:18:16,991
Come on. Move it! Move it!
Move it! Move it!

280
00:18:17,062 --> 00:18:18,996
<i>[Whistling Continues]</i>

281
00:18:21,500 --> 00:18:24,992
- You didn't even shave.
- It's not a school day.

282
00:18:25,070 --> 00:18:27,231
Here comes Colonel Blake.

283
00:18:32,210 --> 00:18:35,373
<i>[Applause, Cheering]</i>

284
00:18:40,418 --> 00:18:44,149
[Blows Whistle]
Company, Ten-hut!

285
00:18:44,222 --> 00:18:47,123
Take it easy, will you, Frank?

286
00:18:50,262 --> 00:18:52,753
It's all set. You're in charge
of the store now.

287
00:18:52,831 --> 00:18:55,095
And, uh, stuff that whistle someplace.

288
00:18:55,166 --> 00:18:57,999
Uh, does the Colonel
wish to review his troops?

289
00:18:58,069 --> 00:19:01,561
- No. I just want to say good-bye.
- Well, okay.

290
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:04,108
- Your chopper's about ten miles out, sir.
- Thanks, Radar.

291
00:19:10,115 --> 00:19:11,946
So long, Hawk.

292
00:19:13,652 --> 00:19:15,984
I'm afraid just a handshake
won't do it, Henry.

293
00:19:23,361 --> 00:19:26,353
Trap, thanks for the outfit,
it's really dressy.

294
00:19:26,431 --> 00:19:30,800
Henry, that suit is really you.

295
00:19:30,869 --> 00:19:33,235
<i>[Hawkeye] If you're Adolphe Menjou.</i>

296
00:19:34,673 --> 00:19:36,402
Gwen.

297
00:19:41,079 --> 00:19:45,072
- You old sky pilot, you.
- Bless you, Henry Blake.

298
00:19:45,150 --> 00:19:48,517
Your work here
will never be forgotten.

299
00:19:48,587 --> 00:19:50,578
Thank you, Father.

300
00:19:52,624 --> 00:19:54,615
Jennifer.

301
00:19:58,630 --> 00:20:01,793
Klinger, that outfit might just get you
that Section 8.

302
00:20:01,866 --> 00:20:04,528
I made it just for this occasion, sir.

303
00:20:04,603 --> 00:20:07,504
I was in such a hurry,
I didn't get the back zipped.

304
00:20:07,572 --> 00:20:10,063
I'll do it.

305
00:20:11,409 --> 00:20:13,502
Up, sir.

306
00:20:13,578 --> 00:20:15,512
There you go, soldier.

307
00:20:15,580 --> 00:20:21,246
Sir, I have a picture of me.
Would you carry it in your wallet?

308
00:20:21,319 --> 00:20:24,652
- Your pink evening gown.
- I knew it was your favorite, sir.

309
00:20:30,128 --> 00:20:32,926
- Two minutes till your chopper, sir.
- Oh, thanks, Radar.

310
00:20:34,466 --> 00:20:38,698
Well, uh, so long, everybody.
So long and good luck.

311
00:20:38,770 --> 00:20:42,763
Henry.
[Whispers, Indistinct]

312
00:20:44,309 --> 00:20:48,405
- You think I should? Why not?
- Why not?

313
00:20:53,752 --> 00:20:56,220
<i>[Whooping, Clapping]</i>

314
00:20:58,823 --> 00:21:00,814
##<i>[Trumpet Playing "Reveille"]</i>

315
00:21:02,727 --> 00:21:05,594
- <i>[Man] Whoo!</i>
- It's all yours, Frank.

316
00:21:07,132 --> 00:21:09,362
# For he's a jolly good fellow #

317
00:21:09,434 --> 00:21:11,698
# For he's a jolly good fellow #

